<HEADLINE>
<P>
LEFTIST PRIEST LIKELY WINNER OF HAITI VOTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Supporters of a charismatic, leftist priest took to the streets today to dance 
and cheer in anticipation of his election victory. Police fired into one crowd, 
killing a pregnant woman, witnesses said. 
</P>
<P>
The reported violence occurred as the people of this poor Caribbean nation 
awaited results from Sunday's vote for what could be the first freely elected 
government in Haiti's turbulent 186-year history. 
</P>
<P>
The witnesses said six policemen firing from a moving pickup truck shot at 
hundreds of people singing a patriotic song outside the gutted remains of the 
St. Jean Bosco Church in the La Salines slum of the capital. 
</P>
<P>
One witness, photographer Lannis Waters of the Palm Beach (Fla.) Post, said the 
truck ran over the slain woman's body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Workers carry ballot boxes from election into the Electoral Bureau 
offices in Port-au-Prince, Haiti. Reuters 
</P>
