<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
DAIHATSU PLANS ITALIAN VENTURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Daihatsu Motor Co. of Japan said today it has reached an agreement to set up a 
joint venture with Piaggio V. E. SpA of Italy to produce pickup trucks and vans 
in Pisa. 
</P>
<P>
The venture is to be capitalized at about $27 million. 
</P>
<P>
Piaggio will own 51% of the venture, while 49% will be held by Daihatsu, 
according to a Daihatsu official. 
</P>
<P>
Daihatsu is part of the Toyota Motor group. Toyota Motor Corp. is Japan's 
largest auto maker. 
</P>
<P>
The venture will build a plant capable of producing 35,000 Daihatsu and Piaggio 
model trucks and vans a year by December, 1992, at an estimated investment of 
$59 million, the official said. 
</P>
<P>
He said the vehicles will be marketed in Italy and other European nations under 
both the Daihatsu and Piaggio brands. 
</P>
<P>
Daihatsu exported 55,500 vehicles, including 870 mini-trucks, in 1989, the 
official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
