<P>
JAY LENO MAKES CALLS FOR GIS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Comedian Jay Leno has been making a lot of phone calls since he got back from 
an October trip to entertain the troops in Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
<P>
"The soldiers gave me about 200 names of all these parents," he wrote in the 
Dec. 24 issue of People magazine. 
</P>
<P>
"I've been calling them up and saying, like, 'I saw Timmy.' And they go, 'Where 
was he? How's he doing?' People are so happy that you call; you feel good about 
it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA121790-0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 324394 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 17, 1990, Monday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 2; Column 1; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
417 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLIPBOARD; 
</P>
<P>
SALES AND USE TAX REVENUES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Orange County cities' sales and use tax revenues dropped for the second 
consecutive month in October, the most recent month for which information is 
available. The October total, $20.1 million, was almost 20% less than the 
September amount, which itself was lower than in August. October's was the 
fourth lowest total during the 12 months. 
</P>
<P>
The amount was almost 12% higher than last October, however, and virtually all 
cities registered gains over October 1989. In fact, Dana Point and Villa Park 
both received at least 66% more than last year. The only exception was La 
Palma, which got about the same amount. 
</P>
<P>
This October Anaheim received the most money, about $2.8 million, but it's per 
capita amount, $10.44, was a little more than half Costa Mesa's $19.09 -- the 
highest per capita amount of any city. 
</P>
<P>
Each month city and county governments and other governmental organizations 
receive payments from the state in anticipation of actual sales tax revenues. 
In the fourth month, they receive a cleanup payment -- the difference between 
actual revenues and the amounts previously received -- plus the first advance 
payment for the next quarter. The amounts listed here are the second advance 
payment for the third quarter of 1990. 
</P>
